(20. A sufficiently comprehensive spec is not \(necessarily\) code) Tj
T*
(Source: Computer Things | Published: Wed, 15 Apr 2026 16:18:02 +0000) Tj
T*
(Link: https://buttondown.com/hillelwayne/archive/a-sufficiently-comprehensive-spec-is-not/) Tj
T*
(Sorry for missing last week! Was sick and then busy. This week I want to cover a pet peeve of) Tj
T*
(mine, best seen in this comic: A "comprehensive and precise spec" is not necessarily code. A) Tj
T*
(specification corresponds to a set of possible implementations, and code is a single) Tj
T*
(implementation in that set. As long as the set has more than one element, there is a separation) Tj
T*
(between the spec and the code. Consider a business person \(bp\) who asks: I want a tool to) Tj
T*
(convert miles to kilometers. Is this a comprehensive spec? Maybe, you can give it to Claude) Tj
T*
(Code and tell it to make all design decisions and it will give you a program that converts) Tj
T*
(miles to km. At the same time, there is a huge amount of details left out of this. What) Tj
T*
(language? What's the UX? Should it be a command line script or a mobile app or an enterprise) Tj
T*
(SaaS? For this reason, if we gave Claude's output to the bp, they'll probably be unsatisfied.) Tj
T*
(The set of possible implementations includes the programs they want, but also lots of programs) Tj
T*
(they don't want. So they now they say: It should be a textbox on a website. Okay, this rules) Tj
T*
(out a lot more stuff, but there's still a lot to decide. React or vanillajs or htmx? Should) Tj
T*
(the...) Tj
